I"@<p>One might reason that if they <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/conversational-interfaces-render-knowledge-bases-into-agents">turn their knowledge base into chatbots</a> or use <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/forecasting-framing-renders-neural-emulation-feasible">neural emulations</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/mental-model-reconstruction-is-like-malicious-face-recognition">the emulations might be used maliciously</a> to impersonate them in certain situations. Crucially, making emulations public adds no danger if the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/forecasting-forces-predictive-world-models-to-internalize-meaningful-representations">training data</a> was already <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/learning-in-public-fosters-understanding">accessible</a>.</p>
